[2] Ethiopia: Confirmed
Date: Tue 28 Feb 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Andnetwork .com [edited]
<http://www.andnetwork.com/app?service=direct/0/Home/$StorySummary$0.$DirectLink$1&sp=l21011>

Ethiopia confirms bird flu
--------------------------
Ethiopia confirmed today [28 Feb 2006] that bird flu caused the deaths of
thousands of chickens in a southern region and said tests would be
conducted in Europe to determine the precise strain of the virus.
Since 16 Feb 2006, more than 6000 chickens have died at a government-owned
farm in the Endibir area of the Southern Nation and Nationality People's
(SNNP) state. "According to our laboratory, it is avian flu, but there are
many sorts of avian flu. To determine the specific type of avian flu, we
have to send the samples to another laboratory in Italy," agriculture and
rural development ministry spokesman Mulugeta Debalkew told AFP.
Samples from the dead birds would be dispatched to Italy over the next 2
days and tested for the lethal H5N1 strain of avian influenza, which has
killed a little over 90 people, mostly in Asia, since 2003.
Earlier, officials said local tests had confirmed the presence of a "bird
flu-like" disease in 49 chickens in the farm, 175 km (110 miles) south west
of the capital.
Debalkew explained that measures were being taken to prevent the disease
from spreading, including a ban on the sale of the poultry and poultry
products within a 60 km (40 mile) radius of Gubere.
Selashi said that some 9000 chickens in the affected Gubere Poultry Center
would be killed starting today [28 Feb 2006].
Ethiopia, along with other east African Rift Valley nations, such as Kenya,
Tanzania, and Uganda, are considered at high risk for the spread of the
virus, as millions of migratory birds flock there during the European winter.
In Nairobi, Kenyan authorities said 400 dead chickens were being tested for
H5N1. [At this time there is no evidence other than veterinary concerns
that these deaths are from avian influenza. - Mod.MHJ]
