[3] Germany: Infected dead cat
Date: 28 Feb 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Bloomberg.com [edited]
<http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000085&sid=aSvuE6PkpO5Y&refer=europe>

H5N1 bird flu virus found in cat in North Germany
-------------------------------------------------
A dead cat from the Baltic Sea island of Ruegen, where Germany's 1st cases
of bird flu were detected, has tested positive for the H5N1 avian influenza
strain, the Federal Research Institute for Animal Health said. Tests still
need to be done to determine whether it is the high-pathogen version of the
H5N1 virus that is dangerous to people, the organization, also known as the
Friedrich Loeffler Institute, said today [28 Feb 2006] in a faxed
statement. The institute is based on Riems, another north German island.
2 wild birds in the southern state of Bavaria also tested positive for the
H5N1 virus, the Bavarian Environment, Health and Consumer Protection said
today [28 Feb 2006] on its website. Bavaria is the 5th of Germany's 16
states in which bird flu has been detected, after the northern regions of
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania, Schleswig-Holstein, and Brandenburg and the
southern state of Baden-Wurttemberg.
Avian influenza was 1st detected on Ruegen on 14 Feb 2006, leading to the
immediate imposition of preventive measures to try to keep the disease from
spreading. Most of the affected wild birds so far have been swans and
ducks. The cat, which was found last weekend near the place of the 1st bird
flu cases, is the 1st domestic animal in which the virus has been detected.
It hasn't spread to poultry in Germany yet.
Domestic cats can contract and spread avian flu, said the president of the
institute, Thomas Mettenleiter, in the statement.
Cat Owners Warned: "It has been known from Asia for some time that cats can
infect themselves with the virus if they eat infected birds," Mettenleiter
said. He recommended that cat owners in areas with bird flu not let their
cats run around freely outside. Wild cats in Asia died last year in zoos
after being fed with H5N1-infected birds, the institute said. Domestic cats
are also susceptible, though it hasn't been proven that they can spread the
virus to people, it said. Still, human infection could not be ruled out in
cases of very close contact with a cat, Mettenleiter said.
Researchers at Erasmus Medical Center in Rotterdam, the Netherlands let
cats eat chicks that had been infected with the H5N1 lethal form of the
virus, the Swiss newspaper SonntagsBlick said on 19 Feb 2006. All the cats
got sick and were able to spread the virus through their breath, urine and
excrement, the newspaper reported. At least 15 other countries on 3
continents have reported initial outbreaks of the virus this month
[February 2006]: Iraq, Iran, Bulgaria, Nigeria, Greece, Azerbaijan, Italy,
Austria, Hungary, Egypt, India, France, Slovenia and Bosnia-Herzegovina.
The spread of the virus in birds creates more risk for human infection, as
people come into contact with poultry during slaughtering, plucking
feathers, butchering or preparation for cooking.
[byline: Claudia Rach <crach1@bloomberg.net>]
